04520nam a22005055i 9780813540979DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20052005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135409797 a10.36019/97808135409792doi  a(DE-B1597)529386  a(OCoLC)875686124  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a261.8/3585/08828992221 aJenkins, Kathleen E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAwesome Families :bThe Promise of Healing Relationships in the International Churches of Christ /cKathleen E. Jenkins. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: "It's Like Free Counseling All the Time" -- t1. Sacred Counsel: "Ambassadors for God" -- t2. An Unsinkable Raft in a Foreboding Divorce Culture -- t3. Collective Performances of Healing -- t4. In with the Old and the New -- t5. Awesome Kids -- t6. Brothers and Sisters for the Kingdom of God -- t7. A Kingdom That Promised Too Much -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aDenounced by some as a dangerous cult and lauded by others as a miraculous faith community, the International Churches of Christ was a conservative evangelical Christian movement that grew rapidly in the 1980s and 1990s. Among its followers, promises to heal family relationships were central to the group's appeal. Members credit the church for helping them develop so-called "awesome families"-successful marriages and satisfying relationships with children, family of origin, and new church "brothers and sisters." The church engaged an elaborate array of services, including round-the-clock counseling, childcare, and Christian dating networks-all of which were said to lead to fulfilling relationships and exciting sex lives. Before the unified movement's demise in 2003-2004, the lure of blissful family-life led more than 100,000 individuals worldwide to be baptized into the church. In Awesome Families, Kathleen Jenkins draws on four years of ethnographic research to explain how and why so many individuals-primarily from middle- to upper-middle-class backgrounds-were attracted to this religious group that was founded on principles of enforced community, explicit authoritative relationships, and therapeutic ideals. Weaving classical and contemporary social theory, she argues that members were commonly attracted to the structure and practice of family relationships advocated by the church, especially in the context of contemporary society where gender roles and family responsibilities are often ambiguous. Tracing the rise and fall of this fast-growing religious movement, this timely study adds to our understanding of modern society and offers insight to the difficulties that revivalist movements have in sustaining growth.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813540979zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813540979.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0 RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0 RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a